[
    {
        "content": "<p>I have formalized a yet to be published proof of the Effros Theorem by Jochen Wengenroth. Would this be a good candidate for the library? The proof is rather similar to van Mill's <a href=\"https://scispace.com/pdf/a-note-on-the-effros-theorem-476vrl1k23.pdf\">https://scispace.com/pdf/a-note-on-the-effros-theorem-476vrl1k23.pdf</a>.</p>",
        "id": 558640723,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1763725642
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is the informalized proof publicly available, e.g., on the arXiv?</p>",
        "id": 558660254,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1763731968
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not yet. It is part of a much larger ongoing work. However Jochen Wengenroth would be happy to upload the relevant excerpt to the arXiv.</p>",
        "id": 558669349,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1763734384
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, the main issue is that it would be poor etiquette / academically inappropriate to publish Jochen's own work. However, if you have Jochen's blessing to do so (preferably publically, so that this is common knowledge), then that's fine.</p>\n<p>As for the question of \"is this a result we would like in Mathlib?\", the answer is \"surely\". Have you contributed to Mathlib before? I don't think I've seen you around. Note that Mathlib has some pretty high standards for contributions, so it may take a while to get something like this ready, depending on how long it is.</p>",
        "id": 558704931,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1763743019
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Jochen has asked me to formally verify his proof with the intent to publish the formalization as a collaboration if it is good enough. He himself is not familiar with proof assistants. I am very new to lean as I just started learning last month for this very project. </p>\n<p>The code I wrote does compile, although I am sure it is still very far from the mathlib standards.<br>\nI am thrilled with lean as a language. I feel it is everything I had been longing for in my study of mathematics. I want to learn more and become an active member of this community. If the subject matter is in fact in the scope of mathlib, I hope I can find guidance here to improve on the work. I certainly am willing to invest the time.</p>\n<p>As for the size of the work, I have written about 600 lines of code, but I am sure it is much longer than necessary. Many of the facts I proved feel like they should be in the library, therefore I assume they are and I just haven't found them because I didn't know where to look.</p>",
        "id": 558711514,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1763744893
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>600 lines is much lower than I was expecting you to say. If you post it here we should be able to give you pointers.</p>",
        "id": 558711724,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1763744960
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Again, I am totally new. By \"post it here\", do you mean as a code snippet in this thread?</p>",
        "id": 558711935,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1763745031
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sure, as a code snippet. You could create a PR, but it will be easier to provide quick feedback here on Zulip.</p>",
        "id": 558712086,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1763745082
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I personally think a PR would be more suitable</p>",
        "id": 558712222,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1763745132
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Should I wait for Jochen to publically approve? How would that look like?</p>",
        "id": 558712441,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1763745203
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If Jochen has stated that his intent is to collaborate with you, then I think you can just go ahead an post the snippet. Either as PR, or as a message on this thread, or using Github Gist</p>",
        "id": 558978681,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1763973540
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Jochen Wengenroth published the excerpt to the arXiv, where he mentions me by name. <br>\n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.00910\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2512.00910</a></p>\n<p>There, the main theorem is Theorem 4.1 (Effros), and the main helper is Theorem 3.4 (van Mill).</p>\n<p>Here is my code. It seems too long for a code snippet, and copy paste to snippet changes white space for some reason. I put everything together in a single file.<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/Jd_7ZeqeH1hCdeSyMWWFJTCP/EffrosTheorem.lean\">EffrosTheorem.lean</a></p>\n<p>The code compiles for lean version v4.26.0-rc2.</p>",
        "id": 561443884,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1764689079
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As I mentioned in the comments, I think I probably should replace the notation <code>U • x</code> by something like <code>MulAction.ball x U</code>. </p>\n<p>On a more general note, I am curious to understand why the notation for the left coset in a group <code>a • s</code> is so simple, and not for the right coset <code>MulOpposite.op a • s</code>. One could have defined <code>s • a</code> as <code>op a • s</code>. Did the community decide against it, because the scalar multiplication becomes heterogeneous? What are the disadvantages of heterogeneous functions?</p>",
        "id": 561447477,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1764689816
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Today is your lucky day:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">scoped</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Pointwise</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">RightActions</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">MulOpposite</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">op</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rfl</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 561450669,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1764690391
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>new version: <br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/rfUV61QW49LwmBrKNSBezK7B/EffrosTheorem.lean\">EffrosTheorem.lean</a></p>\n<p>Thanks again <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"387244\">@Yaël Dillies</span> for the info about RightActions. I refactored the work accordingly.</p>\n<p>I also replaced the notation <code>U • x</code> for <code>[MulAction G X] (U : Set G) (x : X)</code> by a definition <code>MulAction.ball x U</code>, in analogy to <code>UniformSpace.ball</code>. However, since I use the equality <code>ball x (U &lt;• g) = ball (g • x) U</code>, I still would like to have a notation where <code>U</code> appears before <code>x</code>, for example as <code>U &lt;•&gt; x</code>. The equality would then be written <code>(U &lt;• g) &lt;•&gt; x = U &lt;•&gt; (g • x)</code>. What would speak against such a definition? What would be a better notation than <code>&lt;•&gt;</code>?</p>",
        "id": 562453648,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1765196689
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you know about <code>open scoped Pointwise</code>? Along with <code>open scoped Right Actions</code>, this will turn on the <code>U &lt;• x</code> notation</p>",
        "id": 562474679,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1765202689
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"387244\">Yaël Dillies</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Effros.20Theorem/near/562474679\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Do you know about <code>open scoped Pointwise</code>? Along with <code>open scoped Right Actions</code>, this will turn on the <code>U &lt;• x</code> notation</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I am confused. When I look at the definition of the <code>&lt;•</code> notation, the expression <code>U &lt;• x</code> does not appear to be defined in the context of <code>[MulAction G X] (U : Set G) (x : X)</code>. I am not surprised by the diverse 'failed to synthesize' errors in the following code.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Group</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">MulAction</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">scoped</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Pointwise</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">scoped</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">RightActions</span>\n\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">check</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">--error</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">check</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">•&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">check</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">--error</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"n\">check</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">•&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">--error</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 562497193,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1765207825
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh sorry, I see! I thought you had <code>(U : Set X) (x : G)</code>. You can get your thing by doing <code>U • {x}</code> instead, which is arguably not so bad?</p>",
        "id": 562503924,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1765209446
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Writing <code>U • {x}</code> does solve the issue of the order of the variables. It does however come with a downside: the instance problem sometimes gets stuck on the singleton. For example</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">variable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Group</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">MulAction</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">scoped</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Pointwise</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">scoped</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">RightActions</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- error: typeclass instance problem is stuck</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Monoid</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">MulAction</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>At the moment I do not understand why the typeclass instance problem does or does not get stuck on a specific singleton. I wonder: is that a bug or a feature? Why not default to <code>Singleton X (Set X)</code>?</p>\n<p>Here is a version of the file in which I replaced <code>MulAction.ball x U</code> by <code>U • {x}</code> and adjusted the proofs. There are 7 places where I needed to explicitly type the singleton.<br>\n<a href=\"/user_uploads/3121/9bkZbjX21gFCbn_1VoDzwn6w/EffrosTheorem.lean\">EffrosTheorem.lean</a></p>",
        "id": 562526041,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1765216415
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Could also be Finset</p>",
        "id": 562529038,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1765216561
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well then I wonder: why not default to <code>Singleton X (Finset X)</code>, since there is some coercion from <code>Finset</code> to <code>Set</code>?</p>",
        "id": 562529882,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1765216820
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Because you don't want spurious uses of <code>Finset</code> where <code>Set</code> would suffice. In general, it is a hard problem for notation to know what its type should be. There are heuristics, and some of them are implemented but as you are experiencing here they are not necessarily satisfactory. Here I would advise biting the bullet and writing <code>({x} : Set X)</code></p>",
        "id": 562530631,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1765217049
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On another subject, does this snippet follow the naming conventions? How would you refactor it?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">lemma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsNowhereDense</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mono</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">TopologicalSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hs</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsNowhereDense</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ht</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">IsNowhereDense</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">eq_empty_of_subset_empty</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">calc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">interior</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">closure</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">interior</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">closure</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">mono</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∅</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">hs</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 562533003,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1765217879
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would make the proof be <code>Set.eq_empty_of_subset_empty &lt;| by grw [ht]; exact hs</code>, but otherwise it looks good!</p>",
        "id": 562533243,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1765217964
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks again <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"387244\">@Yaël Dillies</span>. I landed on</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">@[</span><span class=\"n\">gcongr</span><span class=\"kd\">]</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">lemma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsNowhereDense</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mono</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">TopologicalSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ht</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hs</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsNowhereDense</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">IsNowhereDense</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">eq_empty_of_subset_empty</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">grw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">ht</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"bp\">;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">hs</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>where your <code>exact</code> needed to be a <code>rw</code>. I also had to switch the order of the variables in order to add the <code>@[gcongr]</code> tag. </p>\n<p>I notice that <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/GDelta/Basic.html#IsMeagre.mono\">IsMeagre.mono</a> is not tagged. In order to add <code>@[gcongr]</code>, one would first have to refactor it as above. Is this a refactor that is planned for the future, or is there a reason not to use <code>@[gcongr]</code> here? Are there other examples of <code>@[gcongr]</code> lemmas for predicates?</p>",
        "id": 562726084,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1765296079
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am now working on my first PR. The first thing I need to figure out is: to which file should each lemma be added?</p>\n<p>The first lemma I am considering is the following</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">lemma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Topology</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">IsInducing</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">isNowhereDense_image</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Y</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">TopologicalSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">TopologicalSpace</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Y</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hf</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Topology</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">IsInducing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsNowhereDense</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsNowhereDense</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">''</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Since almost all theorems about <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/GDelta/Basic.html#IsNowhereDense\">IsNowhereDense</a> are found in <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/GDelta/Basic.html\">Mathlib.Topology.GDelta.Basic</a>, I thought it might be a good fit. However, I would need to import (Mathlib.Topology.Defs.Induced)[https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Defs/Induced.html] first.</p>\n<p>How can I find out whether or not some new import would introduce a cycle and break the project, without trying to build to whole project on my own machine?</p>",
        "id": 562730591,
        "sender_full_name": "Lara Toledano",
        "timestamp": 1765296952
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"987033\">Lara Toledano</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Effros.20Theorem/near/562726084\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I notice that <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/GDelta/Basic.html#IsMeagre.mono\">IsMeagre.mono</a> is not tagged. In order to add <code>@[gcongr]</code>, one would first have to refactor it as above. Is this a refactor that is planned for the future, or is there a reason not to use <code>@[gcongr]</code> here? Are there other examples of <code>@[gcongr]</code> lemmas for predicates?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><code>gcongr</code> is relatively new at the scale of mathlib, so there are many missing annotations. Please PR the ones you see are missing! and swapping assumptions to make a lemma eligible for <code>gcongr</code> is definitely fair game.</p>",
        "id": 562732022,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1765297249
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"987033\">Lara Toledano</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Effros.20Theorem/near/562730591\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>How can I find out whether or not some new import would introduce a cycle and break the project, without trying to build to whole project on my own machine?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Build cycles are resolved first, so <code>lake build</code> will very quickly complain if you have introduced one</p>",
